display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a set, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex> be an arbitrary family of subsets of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigcup \mathcal {B}=X]]></fr:tex> (i.e., they cover <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>). Then we may define the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Topology Generated</html:dfn> by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex> to be the collection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {T}]]></fr:tex> of subsets of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that:
<fr:ul><fr:li>A subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U\subseteq  X]]></fr:tex> is an element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {T}]]></fr:tex> if for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  U]]></fr:tex> there exists a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B\in \mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B\subseteq  U]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ul></fr:p>
 
   
